abstract: BATAVIA, N.Y., Oct. 7.--William G. Wilber died today from the effects of a wound received last Sunday from a target gun in the hands of a companion named William Gubb. abstract: MILLEN, Ga., Oct. 19.--Last night at Ederfield  Broggs's turpentine still Sam Simmons shot and instantly killed Charlie Johnson. Johnson was quietly passing the night in a shanty. About 10 o'clock Simmons approached the shanty, and with one heave with a young pine tree burst the door open, and as Johnson made an effort to get out of bed Simmons fired, killing him instantly. Simmons then robbed Johnson's body of $25, and fled.

abstract: ST. LOUIS, Oct. 29.--Edward Blake, a saloon keeper in East St. Louis, shot and instantly killed to-day William C. Vanderough, an engineer on the Indianapolis and St. Louis Railroad. Vanderough had been drinking a good deal, when a quarrel between him and the proprietor arose over payment for the drinks. Vanderough started for Blake. Blake ordered him to halt, and, meeting with a refusal, drew his revolver and fired at the engineer.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Oct. 30.--This morning about 9:20 o'clock, Dr. Charles Raymond, a twelve-hundred-dollar clerk in the Southern Division of the Pension Office, dropped dead while at his desk. The police were notified and his body was removed to his late home, No. 1,028 North Capital-street. The deceased was about 65 years old. He was appointed a clerk in the Pension Office from the Seventh District of Indiana Aug. 30, 1884, and was promoted the following year.
